arch:property.oc:show_val: Midden from below B.42 in the South area. A priority unit. A small unit for a midden deposit-- possibly not a big deposit? A varied assemblage, including mostly 003-sized bone but also some 007. Moderately weathered on the whole-- the variability tends toward the less-weathered end of the spectrum rather than the more weathered. Probably went and got covered up fairly fast, and there was little subsequent disturbance and no trampling. A little burning but not much, and mostly low temperature (Note: the calcination is restricted to the 007 and cattle bones! Hmmm.); some digestion and some carnivore gnaw. Length of fragments is quite variable, ranging up to 17 cm, and with several fragments in the 10 cm-ish range, although most bones are more in the 3-6 cm range. So the intensity of processing is variable in the unit. Not much cohesion, despite the large pieces. Diagnostics are overwhelmingly caprine, and all body parts are represented. Several fairly large pieces of mandible, with teeth, are represented. One is pathological-- a major infection in the jaw, with a drainage hole. A range of ages. A few cattle diagnostics are present, too. A human mandible was in the flot. Plenty of 003 long bone shaft splinters, and a decent assortment of 007 ones, too; a normal quantity of 003 ribs; and somewhat more vertebrae than we often find-- all but 2 007 ones are 003 size. There are at least 3 left 002 size ribs in great condition that strongly resemble each other-- suspect a ribcage was present. 4mm flot, 100% sorted. Notes from the priority tour: "a layer from the top of the midden. It has mostly sheep-size bones distributed throughout the body. Interestingly, there are more vertebrae than usual. There is a little cattle, equid, and fox, and a marten/polecat size mustelid. There is some hare-size and large mammal. There is a little burning, mostly low temperature, and a little digestion, with several chunks of coprolite. The surface condition is pretty good, and it certainly does not look redeposited. It seems like a classic midden, fairly rapidly deposited, mostly from daily meals. There is a range of ages, with a little perinatal and everything else up to maturity." The flot was over 50% carbonised or burnt, and most pieces were adult caprine origin and under 10 mm long. All body parts were represented except the skull. However, there were 2 microfaunal remains, 2 large mammal fragments and one perinatal caprine vertebra. There were 6 large pieces, over 50 mm long. LH took over recording from KCT at 11347.F122

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
